The Current Problem: Drift
Hydra is not mainly blocked by lack of ideas. It is blocked by distributed authority and uneven status reporting.
Current drift forms: - version and status are spread across README, handoff, constitutional docs, and module-specific docs - some modules are more implemented than the top-level docs imply - some conceptual claims are stronger than their enforcement reality - product framing and implementation status are not always synchronized
This is the first problem to solve.
________________________________________
Alignment Rules
Every section must have the following:
1. One authority document
Not a cluster. One clear primary reference.
2. One implementation contract
Must define: - inputs - outputs - guarantees - refusal conditions - telemetry emitted - audit/replay expectations
3. One proof target
Every section needs one statement that can be proven.
4. One status line
Allowed values: - DESIGN - STUB - PARTIAL - WORKING - HARDENING - CONSTITUTIONAL ONLY
5. One dependency declaration
Every section must state: - what it depends on - what depends on it - what it is not allowed to assume
6. One drift owner
Someone or something must own reconciliation when docs and code disagree.
